{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585452"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:12:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:12:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14976"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14976"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.3,0.03,0.07,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7664"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115423"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7664"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97426"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8094"},{"type":"tags","id":"8113"},{"type":"tags","id":"9976"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18741"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115423"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EImmunoglobulins are proteins produced by plasma cells that help fight infections and provide immunity. Each class of immunoglobulin has distinct structural and functional characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following immunoglobulin classes has four distinct subclasses?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IgG","IgM","IgE","IgD","IgA"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgG\u003C/strong\u003E is the only immunoglobulin with four distinct subclasses: IgG1, IgG2, IgG3, and IgG4. Each subclass has unique properties: IgG1 and IgG3 are most effective at activating complement and enhancing phagocytosis, IgG2 primarily responds to polysaccharide antigens, and IgG4 can undergo half-molecule exchange to modulate immune responses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgM\u003C/strong\u003E exists as a pentamer or monomer. \u003Cstrong\u003EIgE\u003C/strong\u003E has no subclasses and is involved in allergic responses. \u003Cstrong\u003EIgD\u003C/strong\u003E has no subclasses and functions in B-cell development. \u003Cstrong\u003EIgA\u003C/strong\u003E has two subclasses (IgA1 and IgA2).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Immunoglobulin G (IgG) has four subclasses: IgG1, IgG2, IgG3, and IgG4.","IgG1 and IgG3 are most effective at complement activation and enhancing phagocytosis.","IgG2 is specialised for responses to polysaccharide antigens.","IgG4 can undergo half-molecule exchange to modulate immune responses."],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Napodano C, Marino M, Stefanile A, Pocino K, Scatena R, Gulli F, Rapaccini GL, Delli Noci S, Capozio G, Rigante D, Basile U. Immunological Role of IgG Subclasses. Immunol Invest. 2021 May;50(4):427-444. doi: 10.1080/08820139.2020.1775643. Epub 2020 Jun 11. PMID: 32522062."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97426"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14976"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97426"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-